data_alert_description_s: A cookie has been set without the HttpOnly flag, which means that the cookie can be accessed by JavaScript. If a malicious script can be run on this page then the cookie will be accessible and can be transmitted to another site. If this is a session cookie then session hijacking may be possible.
data_alert_solution_s:
The solution for the vulnerability "Cookie No HttpOnly Flag" is to ensure that the "HttpOnly" flag is set for all cookies that are used by the application.

By setting the "HttpOnly" flag, the cookie becomes inaccessible to client-side scripting languages such as JavaScript. This prevents malicious scripts from accessing the cookie and protects it from cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.

To implement this solution, the application should include the following response header when setting or updating cookies:

Set-Cookie: [cookie_name]=[cookie_value]; HttpOnly

By adding the "HttpOnly" flag to cookies, the application can significantly reduce the risk of information leakage and unauthorized access to sensitive data.
